1
00:00:01,875 --> 00:00:10,668
Very often, most often, people think 
that you pray for something.

2
00:00:10,668 --> 00:00:13,046
[Prayer Beyond Pleading]

3
00:00:13,712 --> 00:00:21,061
They’re praying for some
divine intervention in their lives.

4
00:00:23,992 --> 00:00:28,956
A student is praying
that they’ll pass their exam;

5
00:00:29,633 --> 00:00:33,728
different things, 
different ideas are there.

6
00:00:35,013 --> 00:00:38,583
Guru Mahārāj
referred to that as a plea,

7
00:00:39,583 --> 00:00:43,636
pleading,
a particular type of pleading.

8
00:00:44,266 --> 00:00:51,637
And he would mention this
at the time of Hari-nām initiation,

9
00:00:53,295 --> 00:01:02,218
when he would say that
“No plea is to be attached to mahāmantra.”

10
00:01:06,120 --> 00:01:09,646
It was popular 
many years ago,

11
00:01:09,646 --> 00:01:14,338
one particular style 
of chanting in the 60s;

12
00:01:14,338 --> 00:01:15,582
people would say,

13
00:01:15,582 --> 00:01:19,384
“If you chant this mantra
you’ll get what you want!”

14
00:01:19,799 --> 00:01:23,950
But I found out 
something more interesting,

15
00:01:25,011 --> 00:01:30,956
more relevant to my condition,
than I could have imagined.

16
00:01:33,722 --> 00:01:40,417
So herein lies the predicament,
the dilemma:

17
00:01:41,508 --> 00:01:45,905
that when we pray,

18
00:01:50,319 --> 00:01:52,376
who is that self?

19
00:01:52,376 --> 00:01:56,368
What is our understanding of 
who we are?

20
00:01:56,368 --> 00:02:01,144
Who’s submitting these prayers,
or attempting to pray,

21
00:02:01,348 --> 00:02:07,618
or to express themselves towards
God, Divinity, the Infinite, Kṛṣṇa?

22
00:02:08,557 --> 00:02:11,277
So we could say,
just to spell it out

23
00:02:11,277 --> 00:02:16,046
on the basis of some
misconceived notion of self,

24
00:02:16,046 --> 00:02:24,095
we’re envisioning
that achieving something

25
00:02:25,618 --> 00:02:27,987
—whether it be
a person, place, or thing—

26
00:02:27,987 --> 00:02:33,093
will bring satisfaction,
fulfilment, self-actualisation,

27
00:02:33,093 --> 00:02:38,181
self-realisation,
whatever you want to call it.

28
00:02:38,750 --> 00:02:43,635
So, on the basis of some
perceived absence,

29
00:02:43,635 --> 00:02:46,570
a hole in ourselves,

30
00:02:46,754 --> 00:02:57,274
we’re thinking to pray to God
to realise that.

31
00:02:59,182 --> 00:03:03,479
But we’re told that’s 
a lower type of prayer.

32
00:03:08,544 --> 00:03:15,054
Worshipping Kṛṣṇa, praying to Kṛṣṇa,
is another thing all together.

33
00:03:16,407 --> 00:03:22,149
Still, people approach Kṛṣṇa
to fulfil mundane aspirations.

34
00:03:22,412 --> 00:03:26,807
After all, that Bhāgavatam śloka,
akāmaḥ sarva-kāmo vā mokṣa-kāma (SB: 2.3.10)

35
00:03:26,838 --> 00:03:30,694
—ākāmaḥ means ‘if you’re desireless’;

36
00:03:32,346 --> 00:03:38,572
sarva-kāma, ‘full of desire’;
mokṣa-kāma, ‘you are desiring liberation’—

37
00:03:40,212 --> 00:03:44,161
go in the direction
of Kṛṣṇa conception.

38
00:03:44,785 --> 00:03:48,095
Because the devotees know;
they have faith

39
00:03:48,095 --> 00:03:52,017
that once you come in connection with Kṛṣṇa, 
you’ll forget all that.

40
00:03:53,175 --> 00:03:59,227
Who was akāma will be full of kāma,
but towards Kṛṣṇa.

41
00:03:59,630 --> 00:04:05,016
Who was sarva-kāma, full of mundane kāma,
they’ll be relieved of that.

42
00:04:05,016 --> 00:04:06,424
Who was mokṣa-kāma,

43
00:04:06,454 --> 00:04:12,949
they’ll get a type of mokṣa beyond what they desired,
what they could ever conceive.

